=== Routing Prototype

This component uses the annotated pedestrian network both for visualization in the front-end and for applying the routing algorithm in the back-end. The front-end and back-end communicate through an API, which supports the broader requirement of reusability. Separating these components prevents the routing logic from becoming dependent on the interface. This is especially relevant at larger spatial scales, where executing routing operations directly in the front-end could introduce performance constraints. Since client-side set-ups are usually not configured for large calculations. #todo[is this clear?]

The network is loaded from the shared `NetworkSchema` and converted into a node-edge representation using NumPy, while maintaining an adjacency list for efficient graph traversal. his representation was selected because it is conceptually transparent and computationally efficient for the pedestrian routing tasks.#todo[more detail in implementation chapter]

A substantial body of literature exists on “pleasant” or heat-aware routing. So the requirements for the routing algorithm gathered from literature were quite good. In line with previous work the algorithm is an implementation of weighted Dijkstra @rusig_reducing_2017 @wen_walking_smart_2025 @aliyev1_exploiting_2025 @aliyev2_vehicle-pedestrian_2025 @ma_active_2025. With the algorithm having the following two characteristics:
1. The algorithm should account for both the intensity and duration of heat exposure during walking, as demonstrated by Wen et al. (2025) and Rußig & Bruns (2017) @wen_walking_smart_2025 @rusig_reducing_2017.
2. The routing process should not rely solely on researcher-defined weights, as this would impose fixed assumptions about the relative importance of environmental factors. Instead, it should incorporate user-defined environmental preferences, similar to the approach proposed by Novack et al. (2018) @novack_system_2018. 

The first requirement reflects that experienced thermal discomfort is cumulative and dynamic. Heat stress is not only determined by the conditions on an individual street segment, but also by the exposure accumulated along the route. For example, as pedestrians traverse multiple hot segments consecutively, the demand for cooler or shaded streets increases. This means that the cost of traversing an edge is partly dependent on the previously travelled edges.

The second requirement is motivated by the usability of the tool. Instead of only imposing fixed researcher-defined trade-offs between route length and thermal comfort, users are able to indicate their own preferences. This allows the routing behaviour to adapt to different pedestrian needs and weather conditions, without complex daily considerations. #todo[do i actually have extra weather conditions?]

==== Edge cost calculation
Each edge in the pedestrian network receives a generalized cost:
#set align(center)
  $C_e​=L_e​⋅(1+P_e​)$

#set align(left)
where $C_e$ is the edge cost, $L_e$ is the edge length in meters and $P_e$ is the normalized environmental penalty multiplier. This formulation ensures that route length always remains part of the optimization problem. For example, extremely hot but short edges may still be preferable to substantially longer detours, while longer exposure on moderately hot routes should still be captured.

The environmental penalty is defined as:
#set align(center)
  $P_e = sum_(i=1)^n w_i  * p_i * gamma_i (s)$
#set align(left)
where $w_i$ represents the user-defined importance of environmental variable $i$, 
$p_i$ is the normalized environmental penalty associated with edge $e$ and variable $i$,
and $gamma_i(s)$ is a dynamic sensitivity function dependent on the route-state $s$. 

The environmental penalty scales with the severity of the heat stress @basu_hot_2024. These multipliers effectively increase the distance of hot edges, which makes the algorithm more likely to choose a slightly longer route that is more comfortable. 

